bcmdriver.ko.comment: This is obviously BRCM module, but its license is set to Prioprietary thus we don't know the true license just by looking at the .ko file. So we will assume QB is as strong as BRCM here.

browser.comment: This work is derivative of BRCM browser example

libDIALServer.so.0.1.comment: In fact DIAL code is MIT-licensed (C) by Netflix. However they embedd a BSD-2C code there, so... assume BSD-2C for the whole thing

libEGL.so.comment: This is really a symbolic link to libMali.so... so something not really supported by license_checker, so we needed to add libEGL by hand

libGLESv2.so.comment: This is really a symbolic link to libMali.so... so something not really supported by license_checker, so we needed to add libEGL by hand

libQBConax2.so.1.0.0.comment: This is Ali QBCOnax2 implementation, so the name may be a little bit misleading

libUMP.so.comment: Part of ALi DDK/AUI release, contains libump.so in binary form, but this is most likely Apache 2.0 license for the original

libicudata.so.43.comment: Acutally ICU data files are distributed under difference licenses, e.g. BSD-3C, etc. However no idea which carries this data..

libintek_conax.so.comment: Originally this was Intek's code, now heavily modified by QB. So we will mark it QB for the time being

libnig.so.package: Tunner driver for Arris/Vodafone PoC Platform

libstrongswan-des.so.comment: In fact this plugin contains BSD-4C like clauses, needs attribution

libstrongswan-openssl.so.comment: Well, there's a special exception for openssl in strongswan that allows for this GPL/SSLeay combo, so we add exceptions for this particular license

nexus.ko.comment: This is obviously BRCM module, but it's license is set to Prioprietary thus we don't know the true license just by looking at the .ko file. So we will assume QB is as strong as BRCM here.
